messages.content:
CLUSTER:
[
 {
  "riskId": "risk.regulatory-gauntlet.mid-eichrecht-billing-metering-forecloses-german-colo",
  "title": "MID (2014/32/EU, MI-003) + German MessEG §32: billing-grade PDU metering in German colo is legally foreclosed without a legal-metrology approval the entrant cannot obtain in-window",
  "narrative": "Half of this TAM is Germany, and the pitch of an INTELLIGENT PDU is metering. But the moment a colo uses PDU-level kWh data to bill sub-tenants, the meter falls under legal metrology: MID conformity (Annex MI-003) plus German MessEG obligations including §32 registration — a module B+D type-approval path through PTB/notified bodies that routinely takes 12–24 months and constrains the metering hardware design itself. The corpus already surfaced this (Eichrecht metering foreclosure) and noted that serviceableFactor's single qualitative haircut does not distinguish billing-grade from monitoring-grade demand. The kill path: the entrant's flagship feature is exactly the feature that is illegal to use for its highest-value purpose in its largest geography, so German colo tenders that specify 'MID-compliant outlet metering' — increasingly standard as EnEfG pushes operators toward measured billing — are closed to it. The 0.50 DE share silently assumes all German demand is equally reachable.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "German colos shift from estimate/capacity-tier billing toward measured kWh billing (EnEfG cost pressure), and any meter used for sub-tenant billing must be MID-conformant and MessEG-registered — a named legal-metrology instrument, not a product feature",
    "refs": [
     "digest:refine-regulatory-gauntlet.eichrecht-metering-foreclosure#c3",
     "digest:refine-regulatory-gauntlet.eichrecht-metering-foreclosure#c7",
     "digest:geo-DE#c11"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "German colo tenders begin specifying MID-class outlet metering; the entrant, lacking type approval, is disqualified at spec stage from the billing-grade slice of the German market — which is the premium, intelligence-led slice it targets — while Germany is 0.50 of the CE base with Frankfurt colo alone at 831 MW",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:geo.DE",
     "digest:geo-DE#c10",
     "digest:refine-regulatory-gauntlet.eichrecht-metering-foreclosure#c6"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "The effective German share addressable to this entrant is materially below 0.50, and the serviceableFactor's undifferentiated 0.55 haircut double-hides it because the ledger itself admits the regulatory haircut has no empirical anchor",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:geo.DE",
     "ledger:serviceableFactor",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c4"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "MID/Eichrecht metering clauses in German colo fit-out and PDU procurement specs",
    "where": "German colo operator RFQs (NTT GDC, maincubes, Telehouse Frankfurt vendor portals); DKE/PTB legal-metrology dockets on data-center sub-metering",
    "threshold": "MID-compliant outlet metering named as mandatory in ≥2 German colo PDU specs",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "Incumbents marketing MID-certified PDU meter modules as a line item",
    "where": "Rittal/Bachmann/Schleifenbauer price lists and German product pages (MID variants carry distinct SKUs)",
    "threshold": "MID variants appearing as the default rather than premium option in German channel price lists",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 16
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.execution-window.mid-eichrecht-metering-foreclosure",
  "title": "MID/Eichrecht-grade metering gates the billing use case in Germany — half the geography, the core intelligent-PDU value prop",
  "narrative": "The intelligent PDU's premium over dumb power strips rests substantially on outlet- and rack-level metering. But in Germany — 50% of the modeled geography — any meter whose readings are used to bill sub-tenants per measured kWh falls under legal-metrology obligations (MessEG/MID): the metering chain must be conformity-assessed, not merely accurate. A pre-launch entrant whose PDU metering is 'billing-grade' in spec but not MID-certified in law cannot sell the billing use case to German colos at all, and MID module certification is its own multi-quarter, notified-body process that is nowhere on the launch-critical path. The serviceableFactor's 0.55 bundles 'EU cert stack' into one qualitative haircut and never distinguishes this instrument — yet it forecloses the highest-value slice of demand in the largest country cell.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "German legal metrology (MessEG, implementing MID 2014/32/EU) requires conformity-assessed meters wherever measured kWh is billed to third parties — a distinct instrument absent from the ledger's named cert set, which the digest already shows is narrower than the real EU entry stack",
    "refs": [
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13",
     "ledger:serviceableFactor"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "Colocation operators re-billing power to tenants are precisely the buyers who pay the intelligent-PDU premium for metering; Germany is 0.50 of the geography split and colocation plus hyperscale wholesale re-billing spans the majority of the segment mix",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:geo.DE",
     "ledger:seg.colocation",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c4"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "MID module B+D certification via a notified body is a multi-quarter engineering-plus-audit effort; for a pre-launch venture it cannot complete inside the same Year 1 the funnel is harvesting, so the German billing-metering demand is foreclosed for the period, not merely delayed",
    "refs": [
     "profile:Stage",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c8"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "serviceableFactor 0.55 silently includes billing-metering demand it cannot legally reach in DE during Year 1; the reachable share sits at the band floor or below until MID certification lands",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:serviceableFactor",
     "ledger:geo.DE"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "Billing basis in German colo contract templates and tenders (measured per-kWh at rack vs fixed-kW capacity tiers)",
    "where": "German colo operators' published service schedules; DE colo lots on TED and operator supplier portals",
    "threshold": "Per-kWh sub-metered billing specified in ≥30% of sampled DE colo offerings",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "MID/Eichrecht enforcement posture and guidance on data-center sub-metering",
    "where": "PTB publications and Länder eichamt enforcement notices; VfEB (Eichrecht compliance association) docket",
    "threshold": "Any published guidance or enforcement action explicitly covering DC tenant re-billing meters",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 18
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.base-rate-analogy.prelet-lockin-serviceable-window",
  "title": "2026 demand is already specified: the serviceable haircut ignores that reachability has a clock",
  "narrative": "serviceableFactor 0.55 is framed as a channel-and-regulatory reach haircut, as if reach were a static property. But for DC electrical gear, the demand that will invoice in the next 12 months was specified at design stage — the model's own cross-check admits 12-24 month procurement lock, and the corpus shows lock-in occurring far earlier (transformer lead times of 48-60 months, hyperscale cycles up to 4-7 years). Meanwhile the entrant's EU compliance stack (WEEE, CE, TÜV, RoHS, plus EN 50600-compatible documentation) consumes 6-9 months from day 0. The intersection of 'demand contestable in months 1-12' and 'entrant qualified to bid' is a fraction of the static 0.55 — the serviceable share within the YAM window is a different, smaller number than the serviceable share of the market in steady state.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "Rack-power specifications for capacity landing in 2026 were locked at design/procurement stage well before the venture's launch date — the model's own cross-check concedes a 12-24 month lock window, and the growth the market shape describes is precisely this pre-committed pipeline",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:obtainableFactor",
     "ledger:shape.cagr"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "The entrant cannot bid even the contestable residue until its compliance stack clears: the full EU entry set (WEEE, CE, TÜV, Grüner Punkt, RoHS, EORI) is broader than the ledger's named certs and runs 6-9 months, and EN 50600 facility-standard compatibility must be documented for operator RFQs",
    "refs": [
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c11",
     "profile:Stage"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "serviceableFactor 0.55 counts demand that is temporally unreachable within the first 12 months; the effective serviceable share for the YAM window — demand both uncommitted and open to a newly-certified vendor — is closer to 0.35, and the node has no bottom-up cross-check to catch this",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:serviceableFactor",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c1"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "Time from RFQ publication to award for rack-power line items in CE",
    "where": "TED (Tenders Electronic Daily) and major CE colo operator procurement portals (e.g., NTT, Vantage, Data4 supplier registration pages)",
    "threshold": "Median award cycle >9 months, or supplier prequalification requiring completed certification at bid time",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "Quoted lead time for the venture's own TÜV/CE certification slots",
    "where": "TÜV NORD / TÜV SÜD test-lab booking confirmations and notified-body queue quotes",
    "threshold": "Certification completion date beyond month 8 of the launch year",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 16
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.competitive-foreclosure.intelligent-pdu-concentration-shrinks-serviceable",
  "title": "In the intelligent-PDU sub-market the venture actually plays in, Legrand's dual acquisition plus DCIM spec-lock makes concentration — and the serviceable haircut — worse than the headline",
  "narrative": "shape.cr3 = 0.55 is computed for the whole rack-PDU category, and serviceableFactor's 0.55 haircut is justified purely on regulatory reach (EN 50600, ecodesign, CE/TÜV). Neither number describes the venture's actual product market: INTELLIGENT PDUs, where Legrand owns both specialist brands (Raritan and Server Technology), Vertiv holds Geist, and Schneider leads the category — so the intelligent sub-segment is materially more concentrated than the blended 0.55 suggests. Concentration in intelligent PDUs is not just competitive pressure; it is a serviceability constraint, because intelligent-PDU purchases are spec-locked to DCIM/monitoring ecosystems and vendor-certified compatibility lists. Demand written into specs as 'Raritan-compatible' or 'certified for our DCIM' is not reachable at any price. The 0.55 serviceableFactor, built only on regulatory logic, silently assumes all regulatory-clear demand is spec-open — the one assumption the sub-market's ownership structure contradicts.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "Legrand consolidates the intelligent-PDU specialist brands (Raritan AND Server Technology) while Vertiv holds Geist — the intelligent sub-segment's effective concentration exceeds the blended rack-PDU CR3 of 0.55, which is itself extrapolated from a single 15.8% datapoint",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c4",
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c0",
     "ledger:shape.cr3"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "Intelligent-PDU procurement is written against DCIM/monitoring ecosystems: buyer's guides treat DCIM compatibility as a primary selection criterion and the intelligent-PDU sub-market carries only qualitative 'Medium' concentration labels with no share table (Omdia's vendor-share data is paywalled) — so the spec-locked fraction of demand is real but unmeasured",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cust-mix#c13",
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c12",
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c10"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "serviceableFactor's 0.55, derived solely from the regulatory stack, omits an ecosystem-compatibility haircut; applying it drops effective serviceable share toward 0.40 — the venture's SAM overstates reachable demand even where every certificate is in hand",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:serviceableFactor",
     "profile:Product"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "DCIM/compatibility language in CE colo and enterprise PDU specifications",
    "where": "TED tender technical annexes; colo operator technical-standards documents (Equinix/NTT design guides); Data Centre World CE conference specs sessions",
    "threshold": "Majority of sampled specs naming vendor-certified DCIM compatibility rather than open protocols",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "Legrand intelligent-PDU portfolio integration moves (Raritan/Server Technology product-line merges, unified DCIM certification programs)",
    "where": "Legrand investor day materials; Raritan and Server Technology product announcements",
    "threshold": "Announcement of a unified compatibility/certification program spanning both brands",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 16
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.regulatory-gauntlet.enefg-eed-reporting-spec-creep-dcim-lock",
  "title": "EnEfG §12 + EED Delegated Reg 2024/1364 reporting duties spec-crawl into PDU tenders as certified-accuracy + incumbent-DCIM-integration requirements",
  "narrative": "Germany's Energy Efficiency Act obliges data centers to file energy and efficiency data to the Energieeffizienzregister annually (31 March), and the EU's 2024/1364 rating scheme adds a parallel Union-level reporting layer (annual 15 May filings). Neither instrument names PDUs — which is precisely why the model ignores them. But operators discharge these duties through their monitoring chain, so 2026 PDU specifications in Germany and beyond increasingly require certified metering accuracy classes plus validated integration with the incumbent DCIM suites (EcoStruxure, Vertiv Environet, Sunbird) that generate the filings. A new entrant's PDU without a certified accuracy declaration and pre-validated DCIM connectors fails the spec even when its own telemetry is superior — the reporting laws convert the incumbents' software ecosystems into a de facto certification the entrant lacks. The serviceableFactor's 0.55 was set against a product-law cert stack; it does not price an ecosystem-integration gate that binds hardest in the 50% German cell.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "EnEfG and EU 2024/1364 reporting deadlines recur annually through the venture's window, forcing operators to produce auditable energy data — with German colo already publicizing energy metrics (88% RE share) as a compliance posture",
    "refs": [
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c12",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c10",
     "digest:geo-DE#c11"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "Operators push the compliance burden down into procurement specs: certified metering accuracy and named-DCIM integration become mandatory line items in PDU tenders, and the incumbent suites' validation programs (run by the same top-3 vendors) become gatekeepers for challenger hardware",
    "refs": [
     "digest:refine-competitive-foreclosure.oem-cell-odm-price-foreclosure#c5",
     "ledger:serviceableFactor",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c11"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "The serviceable share of TAM for an unvalidated entrant sits below the 0.45 band floor in reporting-bound geographies — and the ledger itself concedes the 0.55 has no bottom-up cross-check to catch this",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:serviceableFactor",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c3",
     "ledger:geo.DE"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "Accuracy-class and DCIM-integration clauses in CE colo PDU specifications",
    "where": "German colo RFQs and framework specs (Frankfurt operators); Bundesstelle für Energieeffizienz / Energieeffizienzregister guidance updates on required data granularity",
    "threshold": "Rack/outlet-level certified metering named in register guidance or ≥2 tenders",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "Openness of incumbent DCIM validation programs to third-party PDUs",
    "where": "Schneider EcoStruxure and Vertiv Environet partner/compatibility lists; Sunbird supported-device database",
    "threshold": "Third-party PDU additions stalling or program fees/queues lengthening",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "EU 2024/1364 second-phase requirements",
    "where": "Commission delegated-act docket for the data-centre rating scheme",
    "threshold": "Phase-2 draft mandating sub-facility (rack-level) energy granularity",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 16
 }
]

Every riskId must appear in exactly one group (as keepId or inside absorbs).
Emit JSON: { rationale, groups: [{keepId, absorbs: [true-duplicate riskIds, [] if none], foldedIndicators: []}] }
